% ============================================================================
\begin{abstract}
% ============================================================================

We present \textbf{brain-fwi}, an open-source JAX-based pipeline for
transcranial ultrasound computed tomography (USCT) of the human brain
via Full Waveform Inversion (FWI). Unlike prior implementations that
rely on hand-coded adjoint operators~\citep{Guasch2020brain,
Cueto2022stride}, brain-fwi computes exact gradients through the
j-Wave pseudospectral wave solver~\citep{Stanziola2023jwave} using
JAX automatic differentiation, eliminating the need to derive or
implement adjoint equations for each new physics configuration.

The pipeline provides: (1)~anatomically-informed head phantoms with
ITRUSST benchmark acoustic properties~\citep{Aubry2022benchmark} for
12 BrainWeb and 153 MIDA tissue classes, (2)~a Kernel Flow-inspired
probe helmet with Fibonacci sphere sampling and face exclusion,
(3)~multi-frequency FWI with sigmoid reparameterisation, gradient
smoothing, and per-shot gradient accumulation for memory-efficient GPU
execution, and (4)~resolution matrix analysis connecting USCT to the
broader tradition of regularised inverse problems in EEG source imaging,
electrical impedance tomography, and diffuse optical tomography.

We validate the pipeline on a synthetic 3D head phantom
(\num{96}$^3$~voxels, \SI{2}{\milli\metre}~spacing, 128~transducers)
running on an NVIDIA GB10 GPU, demonstrating brain tissue recovery
(grey matter RMSE~\SI{59}{\metre\per\second}, +6.8\% improvement)
and skull boundary detection (velocity increased from \SI{1500}{}
to \SI{1555}{\metre\per\second} toward true \SI{2800}{\metre\per\second}).
The entire forward--inverse chain is differentiable, enabling future
integration with neural posterior estimation, total variation
regularisation via SCICO~\citep{Balke2022scico}, and physics-informed
neural network priors.

\end{abstract}

% ============================================================================
\section{Introduction}
% ============================================================================

The recovery of spatially-varying physical properties from boundary
measurements is a central problem across biomedical imaging.
Electrical source imaging recovers cortical current distributions from
scalp EEG~\citep{Hamalainen1994interpreting, PascualMarqui2002sloreta},
electrical impedance tomography recovers tissue conductivity from
injected current patterns~\citep{Calderon1980inverse,
Cheney1999electrical}, and diffuse optical tomography recovers
absorption and scattering coefficients from near-infrared light
transmission~\citep{Arridge1999optical}. All share the same
mathematical structure: a forward operator $G$ mapping model
parameters $\mathbf{m}$ to observable data $\mathbf{d}$, a Jacobian
$J = \partial G / \partial \mathbf{m}$ characterising sensitivity,
and a regularised inverse recovering $\mathbf{m}$ from noisy
measurements.

\subsection{From the pseudoinverse to full waveform inversion}

The foundations were laid by Hadamard's well-posedness
conditions~\citep{Hadamard1902}, the Moore--Penrose
pseudoinverse~\citep{Penrose1955generalised}, and Tikhonov
regularisation~\citep{Tikhonov1963solution}, which established the
template solution:
%
\begin{equation}
\hat{\mathbf{m}} = \left( J^\top J + \lambda I \right)^{-1}
  J^\top \mathbf{d}
\label{eq:tikhonov}
\end{equation}
%
The associated resolution matrix $R = (J^\top J + \lambda I)^{-1}
J^\top J$ quantifies the spatial averaging inherent in the
reconstruction~\citep{Backus1968resolving}, with each row acting as
a point spread function (PSF).

This linear framework was extended to nonlinear problems through
iterative Gauss--Newton methods, applied to EIT~\citep{Adler2006eidors},
DOT~\citep{Arridge1999optical}, and seismic waveform
inversion~\citep{Tarantola1984inversion}. The key computational insight
of Tarantola and Lailly~\citep{Lailly1983seismic} was the
\emph{adjoint-state method}: the gradient $J^\top \mathbf{r}$ can be
computed with only two wavefield simulations per source (one forward,
one adjoint), without ever forming the explicit Jacobian. This made
FWI tractable for large-scale geophysical problems and, ultimately,
for medical ultrasound~\citep{Pratt1999seismic, Virieux2009overview}.

\subsection{Brain ultrasound computed tomography}

Guasch et al.~\citep{Guasch2020brain} at Imperial College London
demonstrated the first \emph{in silico} transcranial ultrasound FWI
of the human brain, achieving sub-millimetre resolution on the MIDA
head model~\citep{Iacono2015mida} using 1024~transducers and
frequencies up to \SI{850}{\kilo\hertz}. Their implementation used
Stride~\citep{Cueto2022stride}, developed by the TRUST (Translational
Ultrasound) group (Guasch, Cueto, Tang), which computes gradients
via hand-coded adjoint operators generated by
Devito~\citep{Luporini2020devito}. The UCL Biomedical Ultrasound
Group (Treeby, Cox, Stanziola) developed both k-Wave~\citep{Treeby2010kwave}
and j-Wave~\citep{Stanziola2023jwave}, establishing the pseudospectral
approach. In parallel, the SMILE Lab at UNC Charlotte
(Lin)~\citep{Li2022brainpuzzle} has explored learning-based FWI
for transcranial USCT, and Neurotech@Berkeley~\citep{NeurotechSonus}
attempted a Stride-based reimplementation but encountered memory
limitations at the MIDA model scale.

While these efforts have proven the concept, they share a common
limitation: the adjoint must be re-derived and re-implemented for
each new physical model (viscoelastic, heterogeneous density,
nonlinear propagation, coupled multi-physics).

\subsection{Automatic differentiation as the adjoint method}

Baydin et al.~\citep{Baydin2018automatic} established that
reverse-mode automatic differentiation (AD) is mathematically
equivalent to the adjoint-state method. The Neural ODE
work~\citep{Chen2018neural} demonstrated this explicitly:
backpropagation through a differential equation solver IS the
adjoint computation. This unification --- recognised independently
in geophysics, optimal control, and machine learning --- means that
any differentiable forward solver automatically provides the
adjoint-state gradient.

JAX~\citep{Bradbury2018jax} provides a practical implementation via
\texttt{jax.grad}, enabling exact gradient computation through
arbitrary differentiable forward solvers without hand-coded adjoints.
The j-Wave library~\citep{Stanziola2023jwave} implements the
pseudospectral time-domain (PSTD) acoustic wave solver entirely
in JAX, making the forward operator differentiable by
construction. Our contribution, \textbf{brain-fwi}, leverages
this to replace Stride's Devito-based adjoint with a single
\texttt{jax.value\_and\_grad} call through j-Wave, gaining:
%
\begin{enumerate}
  \item Exact gradients with zero implementation effort
  \item Easy extension to new physics (density inversion, attenuation)
  \item Integration with neural network regularisers and SBI posteriors
  \item GPU-accelerated forward and inverse via XLA compilation
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Physics-informed neural networks and neural differential equations}

The differentiable physics approach connects brain USCT to a broader
programme in scientific machine learning. Physics-informed neural
networks (PINNs)~\citep{Raissi2019physics, Karniadakis2021physics}
embed PDE constraints directly in neural network training losses,
using the network as a mesh-free function approximator for both
forward and inverse problems. Universal differential
equations~\citep{Rackauckas2020universal} augment known physics with
learnable neural network components, offering a pathway to discover
unknown constitutive laws (e.g., frequency-dependent skull attenuation)
from data.

Our companion project AgenticSciML~\citep{Jiang2024agenticsciml}
explores multi-agent evolutionary discovery of PDE-based models,
while sbi4dwi applies simulation-based inference with normalising
flows to diffusion MRI microstructure --- the same posterior estimation
framework that could replace point-estimate FWI with full Bayesian
uncertainty quantification for brain USCT. The differentiable physics
ecosystem in JAX --- j-Wave (acoustics), Diffrax (ODEs/SDEs)
\citep{Kidger2022diffrax}, dot-jax (optics) --- provides a unified
platform where forward solvers, inverse methods, and neural
components compose seamlessly via functional transformations
(\texttt{grad}, \texttt{jit}, \texttt{vmap}).

\subsection{Cross-modal connections}

The resolution matrix framework of
Equation~\eqref{eq:tikhonov} unifies our USCT work with the
broader inverse problems tradition. The EEG lead field matrix
$J_\text{EEG} = \partial V / \partial s$ is structurally
analogous to the acoustic Jacobian $J_\text{USCT} = \partial p /
\partial c$; sLORETA's normalisation by $\sqrt{R_{ii}}$
\citep{PascualMarqui2002sloreta} addresses the same depth bias
that affects USCT reconstruction. The DOT adjoint Jacobian
$J_{d,s,n} = -\Phi_s(n) \cdot \Phi_d(n) \cdot V_n$
\citep{Arridge1999optical} has the same ``banana--doughnut''
structure as the acoustic sensitivity kernel. Our companion
project dot-jax implements this framework for optical
tomography, and the Kernel Flow TD-fNIRS
helmet~\citep{Ban2022kernelflow} provides a hardware template
for our ultrasound probe array.

% ============================================================================
\section{Methods}
% ============================================================================

\subsection{Head phantom and acoustic properties}

We construct anatomically-informed 3D head phantoms with concentric
ellipsoidal layers representing scalp, skull (cortical bone), CSF,
grey matter, white matter, lateral ventricles, and a simulated
haemorrhagic lesion. Acoustic properties are assigned from the ITRUSST
benchmark~\citep{Aubry2022benchmark}: cortical bone $c = \SI{2800}
{\metre\per\second}$, $\rho = \SI{1850}{\kilo\gram\per\metre\cubed}$;
brain tissue $c = \SI{1560}{\metre\per\second}$, $\rho = \SI{1040}
{\kilo\gram\per\metre\cubed}$; CSF $c = \SI{1500}{\metre\per\second}$.

For the MIDA head model~\citep{Iacono2015mida}, we provide a mapping
from 153 anatomical structures to 17 acoustic tissue groups,
distinguishing cortical bone ($c = \SI{2800}{\metre\per\second}$)
from trabecular bone ($c = \SI{2300}{\metre\per\second}$) --- a
distinction absent from BrainWeb and from the Sonus
project~\citep{NeurotechSonus}, which provides only a pre-processed
velocity volume without tissue-to-acoustic mapping code.

\subsection{Probe helmet design}

We design a transcranial ultrasound array inspired by the Kernel Flow
2 TD-fNIRS helmet~\citep{Ban2022kernelflow}, which achieves whole-head
coverage with 52 modules. Our array uses Fibonacci sphere sampling
on an ellipsoidal shell ($a = \SI{9.5}{\centi\metre}$, $b = \SI{7.5}
{\centi\metre}$, $c = \SI{9.0}{\centi\metre}$) with a \SI{5}{\milli
\metre} water coupling standoff, farthest-point subsampling for uniform
coverage, and face exclusion (coverage angle
$\theta \leq \SI{160}{\degree}$).

\subsection{Forward simulation}

The forward operator is the j-Wave pseudospectral time-domain (PSTD)
acoustic solver~\citep{Stanziola2023jwave}, equivalent to k-Wave's
\texttt{kspaceFirstOrder}~\citep{Treeby2010kwave} but implemented
entirely in JAX. Given a sound speed field $c(\mathbf{x})$, density
$\rho(\mathbf{x})$, and source wavelet $s(t)$, the solver computes
the pressure field $p(\mathbf{x}, t)$ and records time series at
sensor locations.

A critical implementation detail: \texttt{TimeAxis.from\_medium()}
calls \texttt{float()} on the maximum sound speed, which is
incompatible with JAX tracing. We pre-compute the time axis outside
the traced function using $c_\text{max}$ for CFL stability, ensuring
consistent $\Delta t$ between data generation and inversion.

\subsection{Full waveform inversion}

We minimise the waveform misfit between simulated and observed data:
%
\begin{equation}
\hat{c} = \underset{c}{\arg\min} \sum_{s=1}^{N_s}
  \left\| p_s(c) - d_s \right\|^2
\label{eq:fwi}
\end{equation}
%
where $p_s(c)$ is the simulated pressure for source $s$ and $d_s$
is the observed data. Gradients are computed via
\texttt{jax.value\_and\_grad} through j-Wave's PSTD solver.

\paragraph{Reparameterisation.}
We enforce physical bounds via sigmoid reparameterisation:
$c(\mathbf{x}) = c_\text{min} + (c_\text{max} - c_\text{min}) \cdot
\sigma(\theta(\mathbf{x}))$, where $\theta$ are the unconstrained
optimisation parameters.

\paragraph{Multi-frequency banding.}
Following Stride~\citep{Cueto2022stride}, we progress from low to
high frequencies (50--100, 100--200, 200--300\,kHz), exploiting the
more convex misfit landscape at low frequencies to avoid
cycle-skipping~\citep{Virieux2009overview}.

\paragraph{Per-shot gradient accumulation.}
For memory-efficient GPU execution on unified memory systems (NVIDIA
GB10), we accumulate gradients shot-by-shot rather than computing all
sources simultaneously. This is mathematically equivalent (gradient of
average = average of gradients) but reduces peak memory from
$\mathcal{O}(N_s)$ to $\mathcal{O}(1)$ forward problems.

\paragraph{Optimisation.}
We use Adam~\citep{Kingma2015adam} via Optax with Gaussian gradient
smoothing ($\sigma = 2$--$5$ grid points) for spatial regularisation.

\subsection{Resolution analysis}

We characterise the imaging resolution of the helmet geometry via the
resolution matrix:
%
\begin{equation}
R = \left( J^\top J + \lambda I \right)^{-1} J^\top J
\end{equation}
%
where $J_{ij} = \partial p_i / \partial c_j$ is the acoustic Jacobian.
Each column of $R$, reshaped to the grid, is the PSF at the
corresponding voxel. The sensitivity map $\text{diag}(J^\top J)$
indicates total sensitivity per voxel --- the acoustic analogue of the
DOT photon measurement density function~\citep{Arridge1999optical}.

