% ============================================================================
\section{Discussion}
% ============================================================================

\subsection{The unifying inverse problem}

The framework presented here is a specific instance of the general
regularised inverse problem
$\hat{\mathbf{m}} = \arg\min \| G(\mathbf{m}) - \mathbf{d} \|^2
+ \lambda R(\mathbf{m})$. The choice of forward operator $G$
(j-Wave PSTD), data misfit (L2 waveform or Hilbert envelope),
regulariser $R$ (gradient smoothing, with TV as a natural extension),
and optimiser (Adam via Optax) defines our specific approach.

The progression from explicit pseudoinverse to adjoint-state methods
to automatic differentiation mirrors a broader trend in computational
science: the gradual elimination of hand-derived mathematics in favour
of composable computational primitives. JAX's functional
transformations --- \texttt{grad}, \texttt{jit}, \texttt{vmap},
\texttt{checkpoint} --- provide the same operations that took decades
to develop in the seismic and medical imaging communities.

\subsection{Connections to proximal splitting and learned priors}

SCICO~\citep{Balke2022scico} provides proximal splitting algorithms
(ADMM, PDHG) with total variation regularisation, which preserves
edges better than gradient smoothing --- a natural advantage for
recovering the sharp skull--brain boundary. The Plug-and-Play
framework~\citep{Venkatakrishnan2013plugandplay} could leverage
anatomy-specific denoisers trained on MRI data as implicit priors,
complementing the explicit physics of j-Wave.

\subsection{Toward physics-informed neural operators}

Physics-informed neural networks~\citep{Raissi2019physics} and
neural ODEs~\citep{Chen2018neural} represent the next stage:
incorporating learnable components directly into the
forward--inverse chain. Universal differential
equations~\citep{Rackauckas2020universal} augment known physics
with neural network terms, offering a pathway to learn skull
attenuation and aberration effects that are difficult to model
analytically.

\subsection{Limitations}

At \SI{2}{\milli\metre} spacing, the skull is only $\sim$3.5 voxels
thick, limiting spatial resolution. The \SI{1}{\milli\metre} full
preset (\num{192}$^3$) would provide $\sim$7 voxels through the skull
but requires an A100-class GPU (the GB10 encountered OOM during JIT
compilation at this scale). Multi-frequency bandpass FWI requires
further investigation of inter-band loss normalisation. The synthetic
phantom, while anatomically informed, lacks the heterogeneity of
real skull bone (variable cortical/trabecular layering, sutures,
foramina).

% ============================================================================
\section{Software}
% ============================================================================

\textbf{brain-fwi} is open source at
\url{https://github.com/m9h/brain-fwi} under the MIT licence.
116~unit and integration tests validate all components. The pipeline
integrates with the author's related projects: sbi4dwi (acoustic
properties, j-Wave adapter), openlifu-python (transducer arrays,
skull segmentation), and dot-jax (diffuse optical tomography with
the same Jacobian/resolution framework).

Dependencies: JAX~$\geq$0.5, j-Wave (from git), jaxdf (from git),
Equinox, Optax, NumPy, SciPy, nibabel, h5py, matplotlib.

